Dateline 9-17-2017 ANKARA (Reuters) - Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan will meet Iraqi Prime Minister Haider al-Abadi this week to discuss their concerns about an independence referendum in Iraq’s Kurdish region.

Dateline 9-17-2017 ERBIL, Kurdistan Region - A high level Saudi delegation met with Kurdish President Masoud Barzani on Saturday urging dialogue between Erbil and Baghdad as the Region is going to hold independence referendum on September 25, a move viewed as unconstitutional by Baghdad, according to a statement from the Kurdistan Region Presidency The Saudi delegation headed by Thamer al-Sabhan, Saudi’s Arab Gulf Affairs minister met with Barzani on Saturday evening expressing his country’s willingness for laying ground of dialogue and mediation between Erbil and Baghdad to resolving both sides’ unresolved problems that have recently grown in the wake of the declaration of referendum by the Kurdish leadership.

BAGHDAD —SEPT. 16, 2017 — Iraq is prepared to intervene militarily if the Kurdish region’s planned independence referendum results in violence, Prime Minister Haider al-Abadi told The Associated Press in an interview Saturday.

It's really just a question of whether the KRG prefers to use the prospect of a referendum as a threat or weapon. If they held a referendum, at least 90% would vote for independence, so they would presumably have to respond to that desire in some way. This would limit their options, so they have-- so far-- preferred to be all but independent and keep threatening independence.

They are almost certainly not going to back down now. They will want a large majority in favour of independence to support their representatives in the negotiations with the Iraqi government that will follow (and to neutralize objections from other neighbours with Kurdish populations i.e. Turkey, Iran and Syria).
The Kurdish region of Iraq is going to vote on independence. Here’s what you need to know.

The Kurdish people have wanted independence for decades. A referendum is essentially an informal count of the number of Kurds that desire an independent state. They are a key player in the fight against ISIS and believe they deserve independence. With the referendum being held in a war torn region in September, and opposition from every surrounding state, the independence vote will likely take place next year or later.
